MacroLayer-1

Living in Interesting Times

Kunal Goel
Sunny Shi
Seth Bloomberg

Jul 26, 2024   11 min read

Primer

Its clear that 2024 has been a landmark period for the crypto market. The industry has experienced significant developments that have collectively shaped the landscape in profound ways. In this report, we will recap the year for some of the major assets and our analysts' insights and projections.

Bitcoin

  • The introduction of a Bitcoin spot ETF has opened new avenues for institutional and retail investment. The ETFs have been highly successful, breaking multiple records on their way to $60+ billion AUM and $17+ billion in net flows.
  • Bitcoin made new all-time highs after its highly anticipated halving event. However, the price did not meaningfully push past the old highs and is now back below them.
  • The ongoing Bitcoin conference in Nashville features a keynote speech by former President Donald Trump. It underscores Bitcoins growing prominence in the political discourse.
  • On the other hand, the excitement around Runes and Ordinals has diminished. Even the Bitcoin Layer-2 narrative has somewhat fallen off.

Ethereum

  • Ethereum surprised experts and the prediction markets when the SEC approved its spot ETF as well. Early reports of the Ethereum volumes and flows are encouraging.
  • The deployment of the Dencun upgrade, particularly EIP-4844, has helped the network scale with Layer-2 transaction costs dropping to a fraction of earlier.
  • Perhaps because of EIP-4844, Ethereum is grappling with unexpectedly low fees across both data availability and execution. While it is not alarming yet, net inflation has spiked to 0.4% annualized, the highest since the Merge.
  • Additionally, market participants are fatigued from infrastructure launches with high FDVs when there are still few excellent applications.

Solana

  • Solana has demonstrated high growth across various performance indicators, including total fees, dex volumes, and new token launches, as it has become the home of the memecoin mania.
  • Exciting new projects, including Blinks and ZK Compression, that further increase the usability and scale of Solana are being launched.
  • However, Solana has faced technical issues as it transaction demand increased. Additionally, memecoin mania has also cooled off significantly with major assets down 50%+.

With these developments in mind, where do our analysts stand? How far have we come in the first half of the year, and what can we anticipate as we move forward?

Sunny

Ethereum has consistently underperformed both Solana and Bitcoin YTD, leading many to wonder if its now become a cursed coin. The ETH maxi who was once on top of the world, has now become a contrarian. I think its fair to say that ETH the asset is dealing with an identity crisis, while Solana and Bitcoin have found both their narrative stride and their natural buyers.

Bitcoin:

  • Narrative: Bitcoins narrative has been quite simple, store of value and/or digital gold. The immutable qualities of BTC are meant to protect against influential centralized institutions that are incentivized to act based on short-termism, and the need for that asset has never been clearer as the world grows more inflationary and unstable. TLDR: BTC is designed to go up.
  • Buyers: The next wave of BTC buyers are clearly institutions and global entities. This year, Larry Fink has called BTC digital gold, while an executive at Fidelity recommended that most investors should have exposure to it. Wall Street is about selling assets as much as it is about buying them, and asset managers are pushing the Bitcoin narrative to their distributed network of clients. ETF inflows have surpassed expectations, and throughout the year, BTC has traded mostly in line with these inflows. For the rest of the year, Bitcoins inflows will probably depend on global liquidity conditions.

Solana:

  • Narrative: On the other hand, Solana has become cryptos idiosyncratic technology story with the foundation hyper-focused on driving performance gains. Anatoly envisions an ultra-low latency blockchain to facilitate global transactions on a NASDAQ scale, and 2024s memecoin mania has lent some early credence to this use case.
  • Buyers: SOL has been one of the primary meta plays for crypto liquid funds over the past year and a half, with many adding to bags bought below market value from FTX. The interest in memecoins has also made it a popular trade for crypto-natives and retail, partially buoyed by widely followed influencers like Ansem. For the rest of the year, I believe the SOL catchup-trade is still largely in play, as improving metrics continue to make headlines (legitimate or not).

In contrast, ETH doesnt have a rallying narrative nor a clear set of buyers. Historically, ETHs prevailing narratives have been ultra-sound money or digital oil to BTCs digital gold. However, recent upgrades that have reduced fee take rate call both of those into question. Less ETH burned has equated to somewhat-sound money? and rollups taking share means theres a less valuable addressable market for the commodity. The lack of a clear narrative to pitch to institutions resulted in some disappointing day 1 ETF inflows.

With all that being said, I do believe some catalysts exist. With the popularization of ETH staking and restaking this year, I think the narrative can shift towards ETH becoming cryptos predominant yield bearing product outside of less decentralized stablecoins. A highly liquid and decentralized digital bond that sits at the end of the yield product risk curve could find its place into a diverse set of portfolios. If deflationary dynamics return in full force, ETHs real yield becomes more attractive. This value proposition will grow stronger as interest rates fall (with consensus placing that timeline towards the end of the year).

Unlike Solana, the Ethereum foundation takes economic value into consideration in order to incentivize enough economic security. While volume and user metrics are closer between Solana and Ethereum, TVL is no competition. Solana has been the home for memecoin speculation, but DeFi has always preferred Ethereum. Fundamentals have been tracking well for DeFi 1.0 applications like Uniswap, Aave and Maker, and RWAs and tokenization continue to gain mindshare. Should the spotlight swing back around to DeFi, Ethereums advantages in housing TVL and providing economic security would be re-emphasized.

Seth

From a YTD perspective, SOL is leading both BTC and ETH in overall price performance.

As Sunny mentioned, both BTC and SOL feel much more grounded in particular identities relative to ETH. BTC gives many buyers sufficient exposure to the overall crypto market or broader asset class, and SOL represents a potential high-growth platform asset.

At least in the short term, BTC shows no signs of slowing down. BTC is now a new tradFi product, and institutions and money managers, regardless of ideologies, are heavily incentivized to sell it. As an ETF product, its been successful so far, and I see that trend continuing.

While SOL is still likely further away from its ETF launch, it has become the go-to platform for new token launches and, thus, retail trading activity.


Pump dot fun has been an absolute money printer and has clearly delivered a product that the market enjoys. Solanas Raydium has also been an indirect winner from this activity as well, helping push Solana DEX volumes above Ethereum L1 levels. Nearly all metrics are on the rise for Solana, with the average daily fee payers seeing a 51% increase in Q2 relative to Q1 this year. All signs also look positive for Solana as institutions like PayPayl and its PYUSD stablecoin continue to leverage the platform, and new technical upgrades like Firedancer are on the horizon.

ETH, then, begins to feel squeezed from an identity perspective: Is it money? A tech platform? Or something else entirely?

In a sense, Ethereums roadmap may be somewhat responsible for the lack of current identity. Pushing execution and scaling out to rollups brings uncertainty around the Ethereum L1 functioning as a true tech platform where applications launch and grow. However, as ETH begins its ETF journey, firms pushing those products are working to clarify for the market how to properly make sense of the relationship between Ethereum and its rollup ecosystem.


Bitwise, and likely other firms, seem to be bucking the argument that L2s may be parasitic to Ethereum's L1 and implying that they should be thought of as a cohesive ecosystem. Yet, recent discussion around Ethereums lack of explicit (fee) value capture from the L2s that build on top of it brings into question which viewpoint is correct.

Meanwhile, Ethereum is also experiencing a revival with goals of scaling the L1 itself and working towards bringing direct economic activity back to its execution environment. Altogether, while it may eventually net out as positive for Ethereum, this will likely only deepen the search for a coherent identity in the short term.

Dylan

After hitting lows of under $15,000 following the collapse of FTX in November 2022, BTC bounced back in 2024, hitting an all-time high (ATH) of $73,796 on March 14, 2024. Over the last four months, BTC has stagnated in the $60,000 - $70,000 range, despite the Bitcoin Halving in April which historically has led to a surge in the assets price. Bitcoins success in early 2024 seems to be explained by institutional adoption. The largest asset managers in the world, including Blackrock ($10.47 trillion AUM) and Fidelity ($5.3 trillion AUM), launched BTC ETFs in January 2024 after courts ruled that the SEC wrongfully rejected Grayscales BTC ETF application. Bitcoins average daily ETF inflows now surpass that of gold ETF inflows, strengthening the narrative of Bitcoin as a digital store of value (SOV) asset or digital gold.

With no clear use case for Bitcoin beyond an SOV and medium-of-exchange (MOE) for cross-border transactions, cryptos second and third-place assets, ETH and SOL, appeared set to outperform BTC going into 2024. Both assets have developed robust smart-contract ecosystems while maintaining market capitalizations that are a fraction of BTCs. SOL proved successful, growing 613% over the last year, while BTC grew 129%. However, ETH disappointed expectations, growing by only 75%, thus underperforming BTC.

Sunny and Seth have discussed a wide range of narratives for ETH and SOL, which may explain their performance at the moment. A further perspective is that the value of both these assets is primarily driven by their potential to supplant BTC as a monetary asset. If Ethereum or Solana became the base network for global online transactions, their native tokens may develop a better claim to a monetary premium than Bitcoin. Under this perspective, both networks are competing to support the largest digital economy, with the winners native token overtaking BTC as the premier digital currency. Thus, the market may have decided that Solanas prospects to supplant Bitcoin have gone up on the back of consumer adoption, while Ethereums prospects have relatively diminished based on the lack of narrative clarity.

So, where does this leave us going forward? Individual crypto assets vary in price according to their potential to become premier digital currencies, with asset class levers determining the extent of their potential values. Taking an asset-class perspective, the two largest drivers of crypto prices are changes in the liquidity of the dollar (M2 money supply) and changes in the social perception of crypto as viable money. A confluence of catalysts is coming together, which bodes well for BTC, ETH, SOL, and all of crypto.

Consider the following:

  • The US economy grew by 2.8% in Q2, beating expectations and increasing the likelihood of the Fed cutting rates in September. Rate cuts would lead to an increase in the M2 money supply.
  • Both Trump and Vance have advanced the idea of devaluing the dollar to make US manufacturing more competitive with China and rebuild the US industrial base. This would likely increase the M2 money supply and lower confidence in the dollar as the global reserve currency.
  • Wyoming Senator, Cynthia Lummis, will announce legislation to create strategic Bitcoin reserves for the US at Bitcoin Nashville. Trump is rumored to support such legislation. This would lead to further social acceptance of crypto as money.
  • The ejection of Russia from the international financial system and the potential seizure of $300 billion in Russian assets have led American adversaries to increasingly consider crypto for monetary transactions. The Russian Parliament is currently examining legislation to allow international crypto payments for the first time. This trend weakens confidence in the dollar and increases confidence in crypto.
  • Wall Street institutions appear likely to continue socially legitimizing crypto with this week's introduction of the ETH ETF and plans to tokenize trillions of dollars of RWAs.

Altogether, while individual crypto assets may be behaving differently than expected, the future seems bright for the asset class.

About the authors

Kunal Goel

Kunal previously worked in equity research and now considers himself a financial analyst in crypto. He specializes in valuation and bottom-up analysis for Layer-1 and DeFi protocols because he has yet to learn of a way to value NFTs.

Sunny Shi

Sunny was previously a TradFi Research Analyst at a long-only hedge fund. He is now an Enterprise Research Analyst at Messari focusing on consumer, DeFi, and all things cool.

Seth Bloomberg

Prior to joining Messari, Seth worked in traditional finance software and services, and has a MSc in Applied Mathematics. Seth is a Senior Research Analyst on the Enterprise Research team, and focuses on infrastructure, verifiable compute, and the AI x Crypto intersection.

Dylan Bane

Dylan is an Enterprise Research Analyst focusing on infrastructure, DePIN, and RWAs. Prior to Messari, Dylan worked as an Analyst on the Digital Assets team at T. Rowe Price and in Crypto Venture Capital. Dylan graduated from Princeton University where he co-founded the Princeton Blockchain Club.
